  <p class="text-text-secondary text-lg mb-8">
    Fast key-value storage built directly on SlateDB. Simple get/put/delete operations
    with point-in-time snapshots and range scans, backed by object storage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>

  <p>
    OpenData Key-Value is the most direct expression of the SlateDB storage engine —
    a simple, reliable key-value store backed by object storage. It provides the
    fundamental building block for applications that need durable, cloud-native
    key-value storage without the operational burden of managing a distributed
    key-value cluster.
  </p>

  <p>
    Like all OpenData databases, it shares the same storage backend configuration,
    the same monitoring endpoints, the same CLI tools, and the same scaling model.
    If you've operated any other OpenData database, you already know how to run this one.
  </p>

  <h2 id="planned-features">Planned Features</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Get/Put/Delete</strong> — Simple CRUD operations with strong consistency</li>
    <li><strong>Range scans</strong> — Efficient ordered iteration over key ranges</li>
    <li><strong>Point-in-time snapshots</strong> — Read from a consistent snapshot while writes continue</li>
    <li><strong>TTL support</strong> — Automatic expiry of keys after a configurable time</li>
    <li><strong>Batch operations</strong> — Atomic multi-key writes</li>
    <li><strong>HTTP and gRPC APIs</strong> — Access from any language</li>
  </ul>

